President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate two individuals for judicial positions. Thomas L. Kirsch II of Indiana is nominated to serve as Circuit Judge on the United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit. Kirsch is currently the United States Attorney for the Northern District of Indiana and has previously worked as a partner at Winston & Strawn LLP and in various positions in the Department of Justice. He holds a B.A. from Indiana University and a J.D. from Harvard Law School. 

Joseph L. Barloon of Maryland is nominated to serve as Judge on the United States Court of International Trade. Barloon currently serves as General Counsel of the Office of the United States Trade Representative and Acting Deputy United States Trade Representative. He was previously a Partner at Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom LLP and has experience litigating cases in Federal courts and handling enforcement matters before administrative agencies. Barloon holds an A.B. from Harvard College, an M.A. from the University of Pennsylvania, and a J.D. from Georgetown Law School, graduating summa cum laude.